Part 1

The park bench was made of iron slats painted a bright green. The paint had blistered from the heavy Kolkata summer heat, peeling away in long, curved strips that looked like dried snake skins resting on the grass. 

It sat in the middle of Bagbazar park under the shade of a large banyan tree, whose thick aerial roots had grown down to touch the soil, enclosing the bench on three sides like a wooden cage.

Vikram sat there in the mornings, watching the early walkers. He had started sitting on the bench after Sarita left for Delhi with five of the patients who had recovered enough to help her set up a new shelter home near the airport.

"Rehman will handle the Bagbazar house," Sarita had told Vikram before she boarded the train. "He has the entire ledger in his head, Vikram. He knows which distributor is late and which water tap is leaking in the washroom."

"I am here," Vikram had said.

"You are here physically, yes," she had said, leaning on her bamboo cane. "But your mind is still sweeping the dust. Let the boy manage the numbers. He likes them, and he is good at it."

He was.

---

Rehman brought the ledger register to the park bench at eleven. He sat on the hot iron slats beside Vikram, keeping his blue canvas bag between his feet. 

He was twenty-two years old now. His shoulders had gone wider, and his jaw carried the sharp, dry line of an adult who spent more time talking to bank managers and suppliers than to the patients. 

He wore a clean, white khadi kurta, but his shoes were still the same cheap canvas, now grey with Kolkata mud.

"The donations are not enough, uncle," Rehman said, looking at the road.

"They are enough for the paracetamol and the dal," Vikram said.

"But not for the new medical kits. The government supply is three weeks late, and the local supplier wants twelve percent interest on the credit. I told him he is a thief, but he said the bank doesn't accept moral arguments on unpaid bills."

He closed the register, the thick cover making a soft slap. The green cloth of the cover had gone dark near the edges from where his palms had rested during the long hours.

"We need a brand," Rehman said.

"A brand is for businesses, Rehman. This is a shelter."

"If we have to beg for every single rupee of medicine, we are not truly helping, uncle," Rehman said, his voice rising slightly in the quiet park. "We are just waiting for rich men to feel guilty on their birthdays and write us cheques."

"What would you do?" Vikram asked.

"Make our own products," Rehman said, his eyes bright. "The patients here have hands. They can pack medical kits for the clinics. They can make incense sticks from the temple flowers Ramu's nephew brings. Simple things."

He leaned forward, resting his elbows on his knees, looking at Vikram.

"Greed is bad, uncle. My mother taught me that. But need is not bad. If we have to buy paracetamol, we need money. If we have to fight the municipal clerks for the water connection, we need power. Why should the devils have all the money and do what they want, while we stay small and sweep the dust?"

Vikram looked at the banyan roots. A row of red ants was moving along a split in the dark bark, carrying a single grain of white sugar.

"Power is a heavy thing to hold, Rehman," Vikram said.

"It is only heavy when you carry it alone," the boy said. "We will carry it together. The patients will make the incense in the courtyard, and I will sell it to the local distributors."

He stood up, adjusting his white bag. "I have already decided on the name."

"What name?"

"Ummed," Rehman said. "It means hope."

Vikram's hand stopped on the iron slat of the bench, his fingers freezing. 

*Ummed.* The name had the soft, Urdu sound of a letter written on ruled paper from Cuttack years ago. *He changed my name to Ummed.*

He looked at Rehman. The boy was looking up at the banyan leaves, his face clear, his smile open and free of the Odisha dust.

"It is my mother's name," Rehman said. "She told me once that when everything is lost, only Ummed remains."

"It is a Muslim name," Vikram said.

"She converted," the boy said, without looking back. "But the meaning didn't change."

He picked up his canvas bag. "I will print the first labels today. Simple yellow paper. Like the yellow envelope my mother sent."

He walked away down the gravel path of the park. Vikram sat on the bench alone. 

The green paint felt hot under his fingers, but the name *Ummed* was still sitting on the grass between the banyan roots, unmoving and growing in the warm air.

[End of Part 1]
